        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2504798301?book_show_action=true">Sep 06, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dorothy Himberc" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dorothy Himberc" href="/user/show/76362312-dorothy-himberc">Dorothy Himberc</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2504798301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17911673891355245599">Not to reduce this play to a summary like the famous one of The Wizard of Oz - &quot;Transported to a surreal landscape, a young girl kills the first person she meets and then teams up with three strangers to kill again.&quot; (Rick Polito, 1998).<br/><br/>But Le Cid really doesn&apos;t make very much sense. A young man kills an elderly man who insulted his father, the daughter of the victim finds this very noble, and at the same time the daughter demands the death of the young killer for the sake of her own honour whil</span>
  <span id="freeText17911673891355245599" style="display:none">Not to reduce this play to a summary like the famous one of The Wizard of Oz - "Transported to a surreal landscape, a young girl kills the first person she meets and then teams up with three strangers to kill again." (Rick Polito, 1998).<br /><br />But Le Cid really doesn't make very much sense. A young man kills an elderly man who insulted his father, the daughter of the victim finds this very noble, and at the same time the daughter demands the death of the young killer for the sake of her own honour while admitting that she doesn't hate him. (In fact, they still love each other.)<br /><br />I think that all of these deaths were illogical. Nor was I particularly chuffed to read the luridly cheerful war tales involving Moors being slaughtered left and right.<br /><br />But the play was apparently written at a time of wars, and the highest levels of the French court watched it. And it is interesting to read it as a tale about kings and warfare, that was actually watched by the aristocracy and paralleled real life. The question of duelling, too, was highly topical back then, since there had just been decisions made to outlaw that practice.<br /><br />Corneille was tormented with unfavourable criticism around 1637, when Le Cid came out. Even the Académie Française and the Cardinal Richelieu were drawn in. Contrary to their findings, I think few people care nowadays that in writing this play Corneille didn't follow the 'proper' pattern of a tragedy as described in the writings of Aristotle. On the other hand, Corneille's verses don't always make a terrible amount of sense, as his critics were eager to point out. Furthermore, in my opinion, due to the strict rhythm, the lines often limp to the end of the meter, rather than being vigourous, fresh and natural. It is also the kind of style where characters address someone in the third person.<br /><br />That said, while repetitive, the play is not boring, and it at least has an internal consistency and a strikingly different plot. (This plot, and other elements like the characters, were borrowed openly from the Spanish author Guillem de Castro.)<br /><br />I have left this book un-starred because I didn't manage to read it in the spirit in which it was written, and was grumpy from other causes anyway. So I am not the correct person to give the book a fair rating.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17911673891355245599" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

