<div id="review_3790197450" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3790197450" />
    <a title="Becky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7067272-becky"><img alt="Becky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501097310p2/7067272.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3790197450?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Becky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Becky" href="/user/show/7067272-becky">Becky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3790197450" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4904429220126250116">This was a wild ride. Top notch melodrama, I absolutely adored the extremis to which everyone took their lines. Speaking of, if, like me, you&apos;re an Anglophone French-learner, don&apos;t hesitate to read this. I think we have the impression that all &quot;old&quot; plays are Shakespeare levels of wordplay, and this is not like that at all. It&apos;s not simply written, but it is pretty straightforward, and often the play itself will use a word that is more like an English cognate than the edition (mine anyway, Larou</span>
  <span id="freeText4904429220126250116" style="display:none">This was a wild ride. Top notch melodrama, I absolutely adored the extremis to which everyone took their lines. Speaking of, if, like me, you're an Anglophone French-learner, don't hesitate to read this. I think we have the impression that all "old" plays are Shakespeare levels of wordplay, and this is not like that at all. It's not simply written, but it is pretty straightforward, and often the play itself will use a word that is more like an English cognate than the edition (mine anyway, Larousse), will gloss with a more distant one. <br /><br />I rate so low because honestly I could not stand most of the characters, and thought all of them deserved worse than they got, except for poor Rodrigue, who deserved much better. I also remain unconvinced that the unities are good things worth obeying. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4904429220126250116" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


